node.text:
Summer is in full swing here at ADBC, which means Summer Crush is back!
😎😎😎
“Summer Crush” Raspberry Lemonade sour, 4.9% - we start a tart sour wheat base and load it up with raspberries and Meyer lemons zested and puréed in house. The Meyer softness and oily aromatics pop hard on this batch. 

This fan favorite is a refreshing, tart and incredibly crushable beer that’s perfect for enjoying at our outdoor patio, by the pool or with any outdoor summer activities! ☀️
Available in 16oz pours and in 32oz crowlers! 🍺 See you this weekend! 🙌

node.text: Join us tonight at 7pm- either down the street at @angelcitybeer or the YouTube livestream, for ‘Crafting Conversations: Queer In Beer’: a discussion panel focusing on the experiences of LGBTQ+ in the craft beer industry. Hosted by Carissa Sweigart, featuring various wonderful beer friends in the LA craft beer scene, including our head brewer Dave Ziolkowski! Cheers! 🏳️‍🌈🍻🏳️‍⚧️

node.text:
Here’s a couple new treats this week!
“Mr. Popular”😎 Hazy IPA with Sabro, 7.3% - he’s back, showing off the wild and tropical bomb Sabro, this hazy is packed with ripe pineapple, coconut cream, lime zest and a refreshing vanilla/mint herbality.

If you like your dark beers on the crushable side:
“Until Daylight” 🌃 dark lager, 4.9% - mild and nutty with a great crispy lager cleanliness. Made simply with German Pilsner and Munich malts, darkened with Carafa, and hopped with German Saphir. 

We’ll see you this afternoon! 🍻

node.text:
We have a new collab with Dry River Brewing out today! 
"Forget Me Not", Pilsner lagered in Oak, 5.8%
_________
With Dry River being a 100% sour and wood-aged brewery, when Dave asked Garret and Cesar what they wanted to brew, the answer was, naturally: clean American Pilsner. But with some curveballs thrown in, and some oak should be involved in there somewhere. So last December the guys came over to brew and gameplan a foeder-aging strategy for the beer. 

We outfitted our oak foeder with a chilling system, re-seasoned the wood with Plymouth Navy Strength Gin, and sent the beer in to sleep for 3 months. 
What came out is something creamy, dreamy and marshmallowy from that oak contact, with some great floral nectar, herbaceousness and citrus peel cutting through. 
_________
We think this project is a great sendoff for our awesome beer friends from DRB, and we wish them the best on their new ventures. Cheers boys! 💛💛💛
